In article <1994Sep5.081354.1631@ifi.unizh.ch> schaad@ifi.unizh.ch (Rene Schaad) writes:
 >
 > There are many steganogrphy tools. Most use .gif or .jpeg files
 > to hide their data in. Some use audio files, one uses gzip files.
 > Now I'm looking for a steganography tool that can hide data in
 > ordinary ASCII files (e.g. e-mail).
 >


What's wrong with Peter Wayner's Mimic Functions?
They encode a secret message inside a harmless looking
ASCII text file.  This is one of the very few times
the UNIX tools "lex" and "yacc" have been used in
cryptography, as far as I know.

   Peter Wayner, "Mimic Functions", CRYPTOLOGIA Volume
                 16, Number 3, pp. 193-214, July 1992.

As it says in the table of contents of every issue of
CRYPTOLOGIA, "Published Quarterly at the Rose-Hulman
Institute of Technology, Terre Haute, Indiana 47803, USA"
